Comment:
A lot of people are saying that the CGI is so bad, yada yada yada, but all of those who say that are completely ignorant. Did you people check out the history behind the production of the movie? The U.S. trailer was released on November 5, 2015, and the actual movie was released on March 4, 2016. Between these two dates, they were able to edit a lot of visual effects, and many of the unappealing aspects of this trailer were fixed. Don't you just wonder why the gross was more than three times the budget? Well, hell, that's because the movie was appealing to the common people. Plus, don't rant about the actors; the majority of them are extremely skilled and successful. If you want something to rant about, rant about the producers.

And that's all.

Perhaps it's a calculated risk-aversion move by the filmmakers, considering how the rest of the world isn't particularly bothered by the notion of the American president under attack (indeed, why would they be? Who'd be fussed about, say, a threat to the government of Switzerland? Or terrorists trying to destroy the Second House of Lichenstein?) These kind of US-centric films playing on Americans' over-zealous patriotism just don't have the same reach/appeal internationally - so I wonder if that slightly evasive film title will help sell the film to international audiences? Let's see...

Title: London Has Fallen Official Trailer #1 (2016) - Gerard Butler, Morgan Freeman Action Movie HD
Comment:
This trailer is pretty terrible, it gives away the entire storyline. From it I can tell the following:
1) World leaders meet in London
2) A massive terror attack kills most of the leaders
3) The president is on the run with his Secret Service detail
4) A terrorist speaks directly with American control and threatens to kill the president
5) The president says he wants to be killed instead of being captured
6) The president is captured and it is broadcast in Time Square
7) His helicopter is shot at and falls to the ground
From here there isn't a lot to know exact that there will probably be a rescue mission to get the president, which is the final act of the movie... so this trailer pretty much spoils 85% of the movie.

Comment:
"It is the most protected event in the entire world"
(next shots are of the event being easily attacked)
Me: "ummm...."
This looks entertaining but seriously... there has got to be some security protocols against having all those important people in the same location. Heck, they at least keep one guy from the line of succession in some secret place on inauguration day so that if, God forbid, everyone else gets killed, they can be the president. The only reason these movies have even a sliver of realism is the lack of security protocols prohibiting something from happening in the first place, and also the poor reaction times of the agents who are supposed to protect the world leaders. Still entertaining though.
